{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Another interpretation is that, whereas IC encodes feature prediction error, MGB and PAC encode both, absence/presence and feature PE.Prediction error has been extensively studied [18,19].",
    "Although most previous work has focused on the cerebral cortex [18,19], extensive work has demonstrated the encoding of prediction error also subcortically in the rodent [28,40], primate [36], and human [32][33][34][35]37] auditory pathways [28].",
    "Whereas several studies have found feature prediction error in the human brain to be equally strong in the IC as it is in the MGB [32,34,35,37], one study on rodents [28] reported that prediction error emerges along the auditory pathway.",
    "This divergence between the human and rodent studies might be a consequence of the use of different species and paradigms.Responses to omissions have been robustly shown in primary sensory and association areas of the cerebral cortex in humans, primates, and rodents (mostly in the auditory modality [21], but also recently in primary visual [41] and secondary somatosensory [42] cortices).",
    "Responses to unexpected omissions have not been shown robustly before in a subcortical sensory pathway, although there have been recent attempts in the rodent IC [29]."
  ],
